The tomb dates to the early 5th century during the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is believed to have been constructed after Tsukuriyama Kofun and along with the other satellite tombs. While Senzoku Kofun (No. 5) points to connections with Kyushu, Sakakiyama Kofun reflects ties to the Korean Peninsula, suggesting that the regional ruler buried in Tsukuriyama Kofun had an independent network beyond the {{ill|Yamato court|ja|ヤマト王権|12=draft|12=draft}}.

